1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,860
Hi there. I hope you're ready to start using Python to visualize your data.

2
00:00:04,860 --> 00:00:09,285
In this course, we will use NumPy and pandas to store our data.

3
00:00:09,285 --> 00:00:14,490
We will also use Matplotlib and Seaborn to create our visualizations.

4
00:00:14,490 --> 00:00:19,845
Now, you might see the abbreviation SB for Seaborn,

5
00:00:19,845 --> 00:00:22,920
but SNS is considered best practice.

6
00:00:22,920 --> 00:00:24,780
I'll be using that.

7
00:00:24,780 --> 00:00:30,280
We will also write and run all of our code using Jupyter Notebooks.

8
00:00:30,280 --> 00:00:36,580
Let's start by importing our normal Python libraries.

9
00:00:36,580 --> 00:00:40,495
Let's introduce our dataset. We're going to load it.

10
00:00:40,495 --> 00:00:42,665
It's called the diamonds dataset,

11
00:00:42,665 --> 00:00:47,825
and it consists of 53 or 54,000 rows by 10 columns,

12
00:00:47,825 --> 00:00:50,735
and each column represents a feature.

13
00:00:50,735 --> 00:00:55,620
Some are categorical and some are quantitative.

14
00:00:55,620 --> 00:00:58,625
They could be things like carat size,

15
00:00:58,625 --> 00:01:01,855
diamond cut, color, or clarity.

16
00:01:01,855 --> 00:01:07,985
Could also include numerical data such as price or table width.

17
00:01:07,985 --> 00:01:15,325
Let's start by creating a bar chart on the diamond cut variable and let's use Seaborn.

18
00:01:15,325 --> 00:01:17,820
To start of with, to create a bar chart,

19
00:01:17,820 --> 00:01:22,460
we want to make sure or we want to make use of the Seaborn function count plot.

20
00:01:22,460 --> 00:01:28,115
Here, we set the data source as our DataFrame and we list that we want

21
00:01:28,115 --> 00:01:34,270
an x-axis variable and it's going to be the variable in the DataFrame called cut.

22
00:01:34,270 --> 00:01:36,045
When we run this cell,

23
00:01:36,045 --> 00:01:37,665
this is what we see.

24
00:01:37,665 --> 00:01:40,440
Now, it's not strictly necessary,

25
00:01:40,440 --> 00:01:46,405
but this semicolon here suppresses printing of plotting object information.

26
00:01:46,405 --> 00:01:51,470
From this plot, we can see that most of the diamonds are ideal cut,

27
00:01:51,470 --> 00:01:55,375
while good and fair are the least common.

28
00:01:55,375 --> 00:01:58,595
One thing that bothers me about the default settings here

29
00:01:58,595 --> 00:02:01,975
is that each bar is illustrated using a different color.

30
00:02:01,975 --> 00:02:05,400
The cut is already encoded by position on the x-axis,

31
00:02:05,400 --> 00:02:07,670
we don't have a good reason right now to

32
00:02:07,670 --> 00:02:10,595
associate each generation with a different color.

33
00:02:10,595 --> 00:02:16,585
It's much better to start by plotting everything in one color to avoid any distractions.

34
00:02:16,585 --> 00:02:18,890
There are several ways to do this.

35
00:02:18,890 --> 00:02:20,660
I'm going to show you two.

36
00:02:20,660 --> 00:02:26,185
One is to choose a color value using Seaborn's color palette function.

37
00:02:26,185 --> 00:02:29,285
This function returns a list of tuples

38
00:02:29,285 --> 00:02:32,800
corresponding to the color palette set in the function's argument.

39
00:02:32,800 --> 00:02:36,080
In this case, I'm just going to use the default.

40
00:02:36,080 --> 00:02:43,790
You can see here, that this is the array or list of the default colors.

41
00:02:43,790 --> 00:02:46,870
Let's just take the first element from this list.

42
00:02:46,870 --> 00:02:49,320
We're going to index of zero.

43
00:02:49,320 --> 00:02:53,635
We're now going to set that into a variable called color.

44
00:02:53,635 --> 00:02:55,565
Now when our count plot,

45
00:02:55,565 --> 00:03:00,515
if we add the parameter color and set that to our variable,

46
00:03:00,515 --> 00:03:05,735
we now see this much better.

47
00:03:05,735 --> 00:03:11,195
Another way to specify the color we want is to just name it.

48
00:03:11,195 --> 00:03:14,915
Here, I select a very common color palette,

49
00:03:14,915 --> 00:03:17,060
the Tableau of a color palette.

50
00:03:17,060 --> 00:03:19,960
Here we set Tableau blue.

51
00:03:19,960 --> 00:03:23,210
Now, one thing we might want to do with the plot is to

52
00:03:23,210 --> 00:03:26,555
sort the chart in decreasing order of prevalence.

53
00:03:26,555 --> 00:03:32,025
This can be done by introducing a new parameter in the count plot function, order.

54
00:03:32,025 --> 00:03:38,570
This parameter takes a list as an argument with the order in which bar should be plotted.

55
00:03:38,570 --> 00:03:43,180
We could hardcode the values into a specific list.

56
00:03:43,180 --> 00:03:45,980
For example, we could create a list that starts with

57
00:03:45,980 --> 00:03:49,535
ideal and premium and then very good, etc.

58
00:03:49,535 --> 00:03:51,785
But this is tedious and we might have

59
00:03:51,785 --> 00:03:55,735
a large number of different categories for the x value.

60
00:03:55,735 --> 00:03:59,280
Instead, it's better to automate this.

61
00:03:59,280 --> 00:04:05,470
We can do that by using the pandas function value counts.

62
00:04:05,470 --> 00:04:09,680
This operates on a series or a column from a DataFrame.

63
00:04:09,680 --> 00:04:19,670
Value counts summarizes the total number of counts for each category of variable.

64
00:04:19,670 --> 00:04:25,415
It does this and produces this list in descending order of prevalence.

65
00:04:25,415 --> 00:04:27,170
In order to get the bar order,

66
00:04:27,170 --> 00:04:32,195
we just want the index and here we set it to a variable called order,

67
00:04:32,195 --> 00:04:36,495
and pass that into our count plot with a parameter called order.

68
00:04:36,495 --> 00:04:41,450
Voila. Now we have a decreasing bar chart.

69
00:04:41,450 --> 00:04:49,355
Now, one thing we might also be interested in is making these x labels be rotated.

70
00:04:49,355 --> 00:04:52,715
For instance, maybe we're looking to catch somebody's eye,

71
00:04:52,715 --> 00:04:54,200
or maybe we have very,

72
00:04:54,200 --> 00:04:56,785
very long x labels.

73
00:04:56,785 --> 00:05:02,475
In order to do that, we can use Matplotlib's x text function.

74
00:05:02,475 --> 00:05:06,740
All we do is pass in the parameter that we're interested in,

75
00:05:06,740 --> 00:05:09,535
which could be like 15 degrees.

76
00:05:09,535 --> 00:05:11,750
We see that here.

77
00:05:11,750 --> 00:05:14,960
Alternatively, we could also just switch

78
00:05:14,960 --> 00:05:19,165
this to a horizontal bar chart instead of a vertical,

79
00:05:19,165 --> 00:05:21,295
and that is very simple.

80
00:05:21,295 --> 00:05:26,095
We just switch the perimeter x to parameter y,

81
00:05:26,095 --> 00:05:27,810
and once again,

82
00:05:27,810 --> 00:05:31,120
Seaborn knows how to plot that.

